This PR tries to address the issue raised in 46900 where
tf.strings.substr will crash when pos and len have different shapes.
According to the documentation of tf.strings.substr, ValueError
should be raised instead when pos and len does not have the same shape.

This PR add shape check in kernel to allows grace error throw (instead of crash).

This PR fixes 46900.

When x has some dynamic dimensions (typically batch dim), tf.shape can not be constant folded so height cannot be inferred as a constant.
This PR folds this kind of patterns to improve sub-shape constant folding.

[{"sha":"6c526c5153bc350d2a62c7dcbc698be77d3f2439","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Don't shift interleaved updates to separate lane (#20681)

Now that interleaved updates are added to a special queue, we no longer
need to shift them into their own lane. We can add to a lane that's
already in the middle of rendering without risk of tearing.

See #20615 for more background.

I've only changed this in the new fork, and only behind the
enableTransitionEntanglements flag.

Most of this commit involves updating tests. The "shift-to-a-new" lane
trick was intentionally used in a handful of tests where two or more
updates need to be scheduled in different lanes. Most of these tests
were written before `startTransition` existed, and all of them were
written before transitions were assigned arbitrary lanes.

So I ported these tests to use `startTransition` instead, which is the
idiomatic way to mark an update as parallel.

I didn't change the old fork at all. Writing these tests in such a way
that they also pass in the old fork actually revealed a few flaws in the
current implementation regarding interrupting a suspended refresh
transition early, which is a good reminder that we should be writing our
tests using idiomatic patterns as much as we possibly can.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Alan-love/react/commits/6c526c5153bc350d2a62c7dcbc698be77d3f2439"}]

Errors encountered when parsing flags for apply, plan, and refresh were
being suppressed. This resulted in a generic usage error when using an
invalid `-target` flag.

This commit makes several changes to address this. First, these commands
now output the flag parse error before exiting, leaving at least some
hint about the error. You can verify this manually with something like:

    terraform apply -invalid-flag

We also change how target attributes are parsed, moving the
responsibility from the flags instance to the command. This allows us to
customize the diagnostic output to be more user friendly. The
diagnostics now look like:

```shellsession
$ terraform apply -no-color -target=foo

Error: Invalid target "foo"

Resource specification must include a resource type and name.
```

Finally, we add test coverage for both parsing of target flags, and at
the command level for successful use of resource targeting. These tests
focus on the UI output (via the change summary and refresh logs), as the
functionality of targeting is covered by the context tests in the
terraform package.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Skarlso/terraform/commits/4991cc48354275f5a190b12e0f8cdafb952fdc0a"},{"sha":"96be094ecdc9e7c1350aac198c64fa4f5776cfe0","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Merge pull request #27711 from hashicorp/alisdair/fix-target-flag-parsing-and-add-tests

[{"sha":"6c526c5153bc350d2a62c7dcbc698be77d3f2439","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Don't shift interleaved updates to separate lane (#20681)

Now that interleaved updates are added to a special queue, we no longer
need to shift them into their own lane. We can add to a lane that's
already in the middle of rendering without risk of tearing.

See #20615 for more background.

I've only changed this in the new fork, and only behind the
enableTransitionEntanglements flag.

Most of this commit involves updating tests. The "shift-to-a-new" lane
trick was intentionally used in a handful of tests where two or more
updates need to be scheduled in different lanes. Most of these tests
were written before `startTransition` existed, and all of them were
written before transitions were assigned arbitrary lanes.

So I ported these tests to use `startTransition` instead, which is the
idiomatic way to mark an update as parallel.

I didn't change the old fork at all. Writing these tests in such a way
that they also pass in the old fork actually revealed a few flaws in the
current implementation regarding interrupting a suspended refresh
transition early, which is a good reminder that we should be writing our
tests using idiomatic patterns as much as we possibly can.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/zys-contrib/react/commits/6c526c5153bc350d2a62c7dcbc698be77d3f2439"}]

This PR tries to address the issue raised in 46900 where
tf.strings.substr will crash when pos and len have different shapes.
According to the documentation of tf.strings.substr, ValueError
should be raised instead when pos and len does not have the same shape.

This PR add shape check in kernel to allows grace error throw (instead of crash).

This PR fixes 46900.

[{"sha":"d3933f20f7a228eb4f640d9fcb6007c82bd804b5","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Don't shift interleaved updates to separate lane

Now that interleaved updates are added to a special queue, we no longer
need to shift them into their own lane. We can add to a lane that's
already in the middle of rendering without risk of tearing.

See #20615 for more background.

I've only changed this in the new fork, and only behind the
enableTransitionEntanglements flag.

Most of this commit involves updating tests. The "shift-to-a-new" lane
trick was intentionally used in a handful of tests where two or more
updates need to be scheduled in different lanes. Most of these tests
were written before `startTransition` existed, and all of them were
written before transitions were assigned arbitrary lanes.

So I ported these tests to use `startTransition` instead, which is the
idiomatic way to mark an update as parallel.

I didn't change the old fork at all. Writing these tests in such a way
that they also pass in the old fork actually revealed a few flaws in the
current implementation regarding interrupting a suspended refresh
transition early, which is a good reminder that we should be writing our
tests using idiomatic patterns as much as we possibly can.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/acdlite/react/commits/d3933f20f7a228eb4f640d9fcb6007c82bd804b5"}]

forcibly disabled. None indicates the user didn't specify a preference.

is_mlir_bridge_enabled() is False.

This PR folds this kind of patterns to improve sub-shape constant folding.

This PR tries to address the issue raised in 46900 where
tf.strings.substr will crash when pos and len have different shapes.
According to the documentation of tf.strings.substr, ValueError
should be raised instead when pos and len does not have the same shape.

This PR add shape check in kernel to allows grace error throw (instead of crash).

This PR fixes 46900.

[{"sha":"6c526c5153bc350d2a62c7dcbc698be77d3f2439","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Don't shift interleaved updates to separate lane (#20681)

Now that interleaved updates are added to a special queue, we no longer
need to shift them into their own lane. We can add to a lane that's
already in the middle of rendering without risk of tearing.

See #20615 for more background.

I've only changed this in the new fork, and only behind the
enableTransitionEntanglements flag.

Most of this commit involves updating tests. The "shift-to-a-new" lane
trick was intentionally used in a handful of tests where two or more
updates need to be scheduled in different lanes. Most of these tests
were written before `startTransition` existed, and all of them were
written before transitions were assigned arbitrary lanes.

So I ported these tests to use `startTransition` instead, which is the
idiomatic way to mark an update as parallel.

I didn't change the old fork at all. Writing these tests in such a way
that they also pass in the old fork actually revealed a few flaws in the
current implementation regarding interrupting a suspended refresh
transition early, which is a good reminder that we should be writing our
tests using idiomatic patterns as much as we possibly can.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/stackriot/react/commits/6c526c5153bc350d2a62c7dcbc698be77d3f2439"}]

Errors encountered when parsing flags for apply, plan, and refresh were
being suppressed. This resulted in a generic usage error when using an
invalid `-target` flag.

This commit makes several changes to address this. First, these commands
now output the flag parse error before exiting, leaving at least some
hint about the error. You can verify this manually with something like:

    terraform apply -invalid-flag

We also change how target attributes are parsed, moving the
responsibility from the flags instance to the command. This allows us to
customize the diagnostic output to be more user friendly. The
diagnostics now look like:

```shellsession
$ terraform apply -no-color -target=foo

Error: Invalid target "foo"

Resource specification must include a resource type and name.
```

Finally, we add test coverage for both parsing of target flags, and at
the command level for successful use of resource targeting. These tests
focus on the UI output (via the change summary and refresh logs), as the
functionality of targeting is covered by the context tests in the
terraform package.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/pecigonzalo/terraform/commits/4991cc48354275f5a190b12e0f8cdafb952fdc0a"},{"sha":"96be094ecdc9e7c1350aac198c64fa4f5776cfe0","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Merge pull request #27711 from hashicorp/alisdair/fix-target-flag-parsing-and-add-tests

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Adding support to identify a subset of possible auxiliary
induction variables (AIV). Specifically, candidates are gtes, e.g.,
gte(param0, N). We check if the loop body plumbs the AIV
through the same tuple index at root, and that ops involving AIV
involve constants.
   op2 = op(constants, gte(param0, N), constants)
   op3 = op(constants, f(op2, gte(param0, N), constants)
   root = tuple(..., op3, ...)
Further, the ops are restricted to basic math ops (+,-,*,/).

[{"sha":"4991cc48354275f5a190b12e0f8cdafb952fdc0a","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"cli: Improve error for invalid -target flags

Errors encountered when parsing flags for apply, plan, and refresh were
being suppressed. This resulted in a generic usage error when using an
invalid `-target` flag.

This commit makes several changes to address this. First, these commands
now output the flag parse error before exiting, leaving at least some
hint about the error. You can verify this manually with something like:

    terraform apply -invalid-flag

We also change how target attributes are parsed, moving the
responsibility from the flags instance to the command. This allows us to
customize the diagnostic output to be more user friendly. The
diagnostics now look like:

```shellsession
$ terraform apply -no-color -target=foo

Error: Invalid target "foo"

Resource specification must include a resource type and name.
```

Finally, we add test coverage for both parsing of target flags, and at
the command level for successful use of resource targeting. These tests
focus on the UI output (via the change summary and refresh logs), as the
functionality of targeting is covered by the context tests in the
terraform package.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/4991cc48354275f5a190b12e0f8cdafb952fdc0a"},{"sha":"96be094ecdc9e7c1350aac198c64fa4f5776cfe0","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Merge pull request #27711 from hashicorp/alisdair/fix-target-flag-parsing-and-add-tests

[{"sha":"6c526c5153bc350d2a62c7dcbc698be77d3f2439","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Don't shift interleaved updates to separate lane (#20681)

Now that interleaved updates are added to a special queue, we no longer
need to shift them into their own lane. We can add to a lane that's
already in the middle of rendering without risk of tearing.

See #20615 for more background.

I've only changed this in the new fork, and only behind the
enableTransitionEntanglements flag.

Most of this commit involves updating tests. The "shift-to-a-new" lane
trick was intentionally used in a handful of tests where two or more
updates need to be scheduled in different lanes. Most of these tests
were written before `startTransition` existed, and all of them were
written before transitions were assigned arbitrary lanes.

So I ported these tests to use `startTransition` instead, which is the
idiomatic way to mark an update as parallel.

I didn't change the old fork at all. Writing these tests in such a way
that they also pass in the old fork actually revealed a few flaws in the
current implementation regarding interrupting a suspended refresh
transition early, which is a good reminder that we should be writing our
tests using idiomatic patterns as much as we possibly can.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Rachelmorrell/react/commits/6c526c5153bc350d2a62c7dcbc698be77d3f2439"}]

[{"sha":"6c526c5153bc350d2a62c7dcbc698be77d3f2439","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Don't shift interleaved updates to separate lane (#20681)

Now that interleaved updates are added to a special queue, we no longer
need to shift them into their own lane. We can add to a lane that's
already in the middle of rendering without risk of tearing.

See #20615 for more background.

I've only changed this in the new fork, and only behind the
enableTransitionEntanglements flag.

Most of this commit involves updating tests. The "shift-to-a-new" lane
trick was intentionally used in a handful of tests where two or more
updates need to be scheduled in different lanes. Most of these tests
were written before `startTransition` existed, and all of them were
written before transitions were assigned arbitrary lanes.

So I ported these tests to use `startTransition` instead, which is the
idiomatic way to mark an update as parallel.

I didn't change the old fork at all. Writing these tests in such a way
that they also pass in the old fork actually revealed a few flaws in the
current implementation regarding interrupting a suspended refresh
transition early, which is a good reminder that we should be writing our
tests using idiomatic patterns as much as we possibly can.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/manojsdeveloper/react/commits/6c526c5153bc350d2a62c7dcbc698be77d3f2439"}]

[{"sha":"52989a04dcdac271e52f31d7d40bd1c00c4f4f16","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Don't shift interleaved updates to separate lane

Now that interleaved updates are added to a special queue, we no longer
need to shift them into their own lane. We can add to a lane that's
already in the middle of rendering without risk of tearing.

See #20615 for more background.

I've only changed this in the new fork, and only behind the
enableTransitionEntanglements flag.

Most of this commit involves updating tests. The "shift-to-a-new" lane
trick was intentionally used in a handful of tests where two or more
updates need to be scheduled in different lanes. Most of these tests
were written before `startTransition` existed, and all of them were
written before transitions were assigned arbitrary lanes.

So I ported these tests to use `startTransition` instead, which is the
idiomatic way to mark an update as parallel.

I didn't change the old fork at all. Writing these tests in such a way
that they also pass in the old fork actually revealed a few flaws in the
current implementation regarding interrupting a suspended refresh
transition early, which is a good reminder that we should be writing our
tests using idiomatic patterns as much as we possibly can.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/acdlite/react/commits/52989a04dcdac271e52f31d7d40bd1c00c4f4f16"}]

[{"sha":"6c526c5153bc350d2a62c7dcbc698be77d3f2439","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Don't shift interleaved updates to separate lane (#20681)

Now that interleaved updates are added to a special queue, we no longer
need to shift them into their own lane. We can add to a lane that's
already in the middle of rendering without risk of tearing.

See #20615 for more background.

I've only changed this in the new fork, and only behind the
enableTransitionEntanglements flag.

Most of this commit involves updating tests. The "shift-to-a-new" lane
trick was intentionally used in a handful of tests where two or more
updates need to be scheduled in different lanes. Most of these tests
were written before `startTransition` existed, and all of them were
written before transitions were assigned arbitrary lanes.

So I ported these tests to use `startTransition` instead, which is the
idiomatic way to mark an update as parallel.

I didn't change the old fork at all. Writing these tests in such a way
that they also pass in the old fork actually revealed a few flaws in the
current implementation regarding interrupting a suspended refresh
transition early, which is a good reminder that we should be writing our
tests using idiomatic patterns as much as we possibly can.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/chojar/react/commits/6c526c5153bc350d2a62c7dcbc698be77d3f2439"}]

Errors encountered when parsing flags for apply, plan, and refresh were
being suppressed. This resulted in a generic usage error when using an
invalid `-target` flag.

This commit makes several changes to address this. First, these commands
now output the flag parse error before exiting, leaving at least some
hint about the error. You can verify this manually with something like:

    terraform apply -invalid-flag

We also change how target attributes are parsed, moving the
responsibility from the flags instance to the command. This allows us to
customize the diagnostic output to be more user friendly. The
diagnostics now look like:

```shellsession
$ terraform apply -no-color -target=foo

Error: Invalid target "foo"

Resource specification must include a resource type and name.
```

Finally, we add test coverage for both parsing of target flags, and at
the command level for successful use of resource targeting. These tests
focus on the UI output (via the change summary and refresh logs), as the
functionality of targeting is covered by the context tests in the
terraform package.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tokyo2006/terraform/commits/4991cc48354275f5a190b12e0f8cdafb952fdc0a"},{"sha":"96be094ecdc9e7c1350aac198c64fa4f5776cfe0","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Merge pull request #27711 from hashicorp/alisdair/fix-target-flag-parsing-and-add-tests

tf.strings.substr will crash when pos and len have different shapes.
According to the documentation of tf.strings.substr, ValueError
should be raised instead when pos and len does not have the same shape.

This PR add shape check in kernel to allows grace error throw (instead of crash).

This PR fixes 46900.

[{"sha":"bd50e04e660196c68a91155ea6eb5588fdd0adbd","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Don't shift interleaved updates to separate lane

Now that interleaved updates are added to a special queue, we no longer
need to shift them into their own lane. We can add to a lane that's
already in the middle of rendering without risk of tearing.

See #20615 for more background.

I've only changed this in the new fork, and only behind the
enableTransitionEntanglements flag.

Most of this commit involves updating tests. The "shift-to-a-new" lane
trick was intentionally used in a handful of tests where two or more
updates need to be scheduled in different lanes. Most of these tests
were written before `startTransition` existed, and all of them were
written before transitions were assigned arbitrary lanes.

So I ported these tests to use `startTransition` instead, which is the
idiomatic way to mark an update as parallel.

I didn't change the old fork at all. Writing these tests in such a way
that they also pass in the old fork actually revealed a few flaws in the
current implementation regarding interrupting a suspended refresh
transition early, which is a good reminder that we should be writing our
tests using idiomatic patterns as much as we possibly can.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/acdlite/react/commits/bd50e04e660196c68a91155ea6eb5588fdd0adbd"}]

[{"sha":"6c526c5153bc350d2a62c7dcbc698be77d3f2439","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Don't shift interleaved updates to separate lane (#20681)

Now that interleaved updates are added to a special queue, we no longer
need to shift them into their own lane. We can add to a lane that's
already in the middle of rendering without risk of tearing.

See #20615 for more background.

I've only changed this in the new fork, and only behind the
enableTransitionEntanglements flag.

Most of this commit involves updating tests. The "shift-to-a-new" lane
trick was intentionally used in a handful of tests where two or more
updates need to be scheduled in different lanes. Most of these tests
were written before `startTransition` existed, and all of them were
written before transitions were assigned arbitrary lanes.

So I ported these tests to use `startTransition` instead, which is the
idiomatic way to mark an update as parallel.

I didn't change the old fork at all. Writing these tests in such a way
that they also pass in the old fork actually revealed a few flaws in the
current implementation regarding interrupting a suspended refresh
transition early, which is a good reminder that we should be writing our
tests using idiomatic patterns as much as we possibly can.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/facebook/react/commits/6c526c5153bc350d2a62c7dcbc698be77d3f2439"}]

This PR is part of the effort to switch to modular file system support
by deprecates hdfs file system and direct user to use modular file system
from tensorflow-io instead.

[{"sha":"a014c915c77f908ba3be3de9e6a06d05c71d5b62","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Parallel transitions: Assign different lanes to consecutive transitions (#20672)

* Land enableTransitionEntanglement changes

Leaving the flag though because I plan to reuse it for additional,
similar changes.

* Assign different lanes to consecutive transitions

Currently we always assign the same lane to all transitions. This means
if there are two pending transitions at the same time, neither
transition can finish until both can finish, even if they affect
completely separate parts of the UI.

The new approach is to assign a different lane to each consecutive
transition, by shifting the bit to the right each time. When we reach
the end of the bit range, we cycle back to the first bit. In practice,
this should mean that all transitions get their own dedicated lane,
unless we have more pending transitions than lanes, which should
be rare.

We retain our existing behavior of assigning the same lane to all
transitions within the same event. This is achieved by caching the first
lane assigned to a transition, then re-using that one until the next
React task, by which point the event must have finished. This preserves
the guarantee that all transition updates that result from a single
event will be consistent.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Rachelmorrell/react/commits/a014c915c77f908ba3be3de9e6a06d05c71d5b62"},{"sha":"b4658f2daa4990ef8057335cd7202b479bd8d41a","author":{"name":"Dan Abramov","email":"ffbbe9cb1097e7ea6a3dedffde5b4fe769829acc@gmail.com"},"message":"Reduce some constant duplication (#20761)

[{"sha":"2a11231e3b609a0f0c70d430c850fee01c58c344","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Don't shift interleaved updates to separate lane

Now that interleaved updates are added to a special queue, we no longer
need to shift them into their own lane. We can add to a lane that's
already in the middle of rendering without risk of tearing.

See #20615 for more background.

I've only changed this in the new fork, and only behind the
enableTransitionEntanglements flag.

Most of this commit involves updating tests. The "shift-to-a-new" lane
trick was intentionally used in a handful of tests where two or more
updates need to be scheduled in different lanes. Most of these tests
were written before `startTransition` existed, and all of them were
written before transitions were assigned arbitrary lanes.

So I ported these tests to use `startTransition` instead, which is the
idiomatic way to mark an update as parallel.

I didn't change the old fork at all. Writing these tests in such a way
that they also pass in the old fork actually revealed a few flaws in the
current implementation regarding interrupting a suspended refresh
transition early, which is a good reminder that we should be writing our
tests using idiomatic patterns as much as we possibly can.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/acdlite/react/commits/2a11231e3b609a0f0c70d430c850fee01c58c344"}]

[{"sha":"6c526c5153bc350d2a62c7dcbc698be77d3f2439","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Don't shift interleaved updates to separate lane (#20681)

Now that interleaved updates are added to a special queue, we no longer
need to shift them into their own lane. We can add to a lane that's
already in the middle of rendering without risk of tearing.

See #20615 for more background.

I've only changed this in the new fork, and only behind the
enableTransitionEntanglements flag.

Most of this commit involves updating tests. The "shift-to-a-new" lane
trick was intentionally used in a handful of tests where two or more
updates need to be scheduled in different lanes. Most of these tests
were written before `startTransition` existed, and all of them were
written before transitions were assigned arbitrary lanes.

So I ported these tests to use `startTransition` instead, which is the
idiomatic way to mark an update as parallel.

I didn't change the old fork at all. Writing these tests in such a way
that they also pass in the old fork actually revealed a few flaws in the
current implementation regarding interrupting a suspended refresh
transition early, which is a good reminder that we should be writing our
tests using idiomatic patterns as much as we possibly can.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/rafsanulhasan/react/commits/6c526c5153bc350d2a62c7dcbc698be77d3f2439"}]

[{"sha":"4991cc48354275f5a190b12e0f8cdafb952fdc0a","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"cli: Improve error for invalid -target flags

Errors encountered when parsing flags for apply, plan, and refresh were
being suppressed. This resulted in a generic usage error when using an
invalid `-target` flag.

This commit makes several changes to address this. First, these commands
now output the flag parse error before exiting, leaving at least some
hint about the error. You can verify this manually with something like:

    terraform apply -invalid-flag

We also change how target attributes are parsed, moving the
responsibility from the flags instance to the command. This allows us to
customize the diagnostic output to be more user friendly. The
diagnostics now look like:

```shellsession
$ terraform apply -no-color -target=foo

Error: Invalid target "foo"

Resource specification must include a resource type and name.
```

Finally, we add test coverage for both parsing of target flags, and at
the command level for successful use of resource targeting. These tests
focus on the UI output (via the change summary and refresh logs), as the
functionality of targeting is covered by the context tests in the
terraform package.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/rpatil524/terraform/commits/4991cc48354275f5a190b12e0f8cdafb952fdc0a"},{"sha":"96be094ecdc9e7c1350aac198c64fa4f5776cfe0","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Merge pull request #27711 from hashicorp/alisdair/fix-target-flag-parsing-and-add-tests

[{"sha":"6c526c5153bc350d2a62c7dcbc698be77d3f2439","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Don't shift interleaved updates to separate lane (#20681)

Now that interleaved updates are added to a special queue, we no longer
need to shift them into their own lane. We can add to a lane that's
already in the middle of rendering without risk of tearing.

See #20615 for more background.

I've only changed this in the new fork, and only behind the
enableTransitionEntanglements flag.

Most of this commit involves updating tests. The "shift-to-a-new" lane
trick was intentionally used in a handful of tests where two or more
updates need to be scheduled in different lanes. Most of these tests
were written before `startTransition` existed, and all of them were
written before transitions were assigned arbitrary lanes.

So I ported these tests to use `startTransition` instead, which is the
idiomatic way to mark an update as parallel.

I didn't change the old fork at all. Writing these tests in such a way
that they also pass in the old fork actually revealed a few flaws in the

The documentation for validate_vendor_used in hack/validate/vendor states
that a warning will be emitted if license information cannot be found in
a vendored package. However, because the script is run with pipefail set
(owing to the inclusion of the common validation script .validate) and
`grep -c` is used, the entire script will fail whenever license information
cannot be found in a vendored package.

[{"sha":"4991cc48354275f5a190b12e0f8cdafb952fdc0a","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"cli: Improve error for invalid -target flags

Errors encountered when parsing flags for apply, plan, and refresh were
being suppressed. This resulted in a generic usage error when using an
invalid `-target` flag.

This commit makes several changes to address this. First, these commands
now output the flag parse error before exiting, leaving at least some
hint about the error. You can verify this manually with something like:

    terraform apply -invalid-flag

We also change how target attributes are parsed, moving the
responsibility from the flags instance to the command. This allows us to
customize the diagnostic output to be more user friendly. The
diagnostics now look like:

```shellsession
$ terraform apply -no-color -target=foo

Error: Invalid target "foo"

Resource specification must include a resource type and name.
```

Finally, we add test coverage for both parsing of target flags, and at
the command level for successful use of resource targeting. These tests
focus on the UI output (via the change summary and refresh logs), as the
functionality of targeting is covered by the context tests in the
terraform package.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/waterdrops/terraform/commits/4991cc48354275f5a190b12e0f8cdafb952fdc0a"},{"sha":"96be094ecdc9e7c1350aac198c64fa4f5776cfe0","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Merge pull request #27711 from hashicorp/alisdair/fix-target-flag-parsing-and-add-tests

The goal is to simplify our CI pipeline so that all configurations
are built and tested in a single workflow.

As a first step, this adds a new build script entry point that builds
both the experimental and stable release channels into a single
artifacts directory.

The script works by wrapping the existing build script (which only
builds a single release channel at a time), then post-processing the
results to match the desired filesystem layout. A future version of the
build script would output the files directly without post-processing.

Because many parts of our infra depend on the existing layout of the
build artifacts directory, I have left the old workflows untouched.
We can incremental migrate to the new layout, then delete the old
workflows after we've finished.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/DerrickCN/react/commits/eb0fb382308f18460844d646dada2e564f82353d"},{"sha":"9a6a41d108e1bb7c4babebebad7e72daa22a2374","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Migrate build tests to combined workflow (#20574)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/DerrickCN/react/commits/9a6a41d108e1bb7c4babebebad7e72daa22a2374"},{"sha":"b99ac3d6dffbe57f94d368cc4f4e0ddf089e4f53","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Migrate remaining tests to combined workflow (#20577)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/DerrickCN/react/commits/b99ac3d6dffbe57f94d368cc4f4e0ddf089e4f53"},{"sha":"e6ed2bcf424d0a25a8f628f7bb9962a29ec7d88f","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Update package.json versions as part of build step (#20579)

We need to call `detachFiberAfterEffects` on the fiber's alternate to
clean it up. We're currently not, because the `alternate` field is
cleared during `detachFiberMutation`. So I deferred detaching the
`alternate` until the passive phase. Only the `return` pointer needs to
be detached for semantic purposes.

I don't think there's any good way to test this without using
reflection. It's not even observable using out our "supported"
reflection APIs (`findDOMNode`), or at least not that I can think of.
Which is a good thing, in a way.

It's not really a memory leak, either, because the only reference to the
alternate fiber is from the parent's alternate. Which will be
disconnected the next time the parent is updated or deleted.

It's really only observable if you mess around with internals in ways
you're not supposed to — I found it because a product test in www that
uses Enzyme was doing just that.

In lieu of a new unit test, I confirmed this patch fixes the broken
product test.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/DerrickCN/react/commits/42e04b46d19648968537a404f15cebc42b6fab54"},{"sha":"98313aaa7ea58d49eb30ecffc0f9eb6fc1ef467a","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Migrate prepare-release-from-ci to new workflow (#20581)

DevTools was built with a fork of an early idea for how Suspense cache might work. This idea is incompatible with newer APIs like `useTransition` which unfortunately prevented me from making certain UX improvements. This PR swaps out the primary usage of this cache (there are a few) in favor of the newer `unstable_getCacheForType` and `unstable_useCacheRefresh` APIs. We can go back and update the others in follow up PRs.

### Messaging changes

I've refactored the way the frontend loads component props/state/etc to hopefully make it better match the Suspense+cache model. Doing this gave up some of the small optimizations I'd added but hopefully the actual performance impact of that is minor and the overall ergonomic improvements of working with the cache API make this worth it.

The backend no longer remembers inspected paths. Instead, the frontend sends them every time and the backend sends a response with those paths. I've also added a new "force" parameter that the frontend can use to tell the backend to send a response even if the component hasn't rendered since the last time it asked. (This is used to get data for newly inspected paths.)

_Initial inspection..._
```
front |                                                      | back
      | -- "inspect" (id:1, paths:[], force:true) ---------> |
      | <------------------------ "inspected" (full-data) -- |
```
_1 second passes with no updates..._
```
      | -- "inspect" (id:1, paths:[], force:false) --------> |
      | <------------------------ "inspected" (no-change) -- |
```
_User clicks to expand a path, aka hydrate..._
```
      | -- "inspect" (id:1, paths:['foo'], force:true) ----> |
      | <------------------------ "inspected" (full-data) -- |
```
_1 second passes during which there is an update..._
```
      | -- "inspect" (id:1, paths:['foo'], force:false) ---> |
      | <----------------- "inspectedElement" (full-data) -- |
```

### Clear errors/warnings transition
Previously this meant there would be a delay after clicking the "clear" button. The UX after this change is much improved.

### Hydrating paths transition
I also added a transition to hydration (expanding "dehyrated" paths).

### Better error boundaries
I also added a lower-level error boundary in case the new suspense operation ever failed. It provides a better "retry" mechanism (select a new element) so DevTools doesn't become entirely useful. Here I'm intentionally causing an error every time I select an element.

### Improved snapshot tests
I also migrated several of the existing snapshot tests to use inline snapshots and added a new serializer for dehydrated props. Inline snapshots are easier to verify and maintain and the new serializer means dehydrated props will be formatted in a way that makes sense rather than being empty (in external snapshots) or super verbose (default inline snapshot format).","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/DerrickCN/react/commits/af16f755dc7e0d6e2b4bf79b86c434f4ce0497fe"},{"sha":"ba9582da27481677cdac2dd000a438147a5df88e","author":{"name":"ChenLei","email":"2078e632128f17c4aa4e413d134a36c7418bccff@qq.com"},"message":"[devtools] Fix can't expand prop value in some scenario (#20534)

The pattern is common is TF python library like height = tf.shape(x)[1].
When x has some dynamic dimensions (typically batch dim), tf.shape can not be constant folded so height cannot be inferred as a constant.

[{"sha":"6c526c5153bc350d2a62c7dcbc698be77d3f2439","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Don't shift interleaved updates to separate lane (#20681)

Now that interleaved updates are added to a special queue, we no longer
need to shift them into their own lane. We can add to a lane that's
already in the middle of rendering without risk of tearing.

See #20615 for more background.

I've only changed this in the new fork, and only behind the
enableTransitionEntanglements flag.

Most of this commit involves updating tests. The "shift-to-a-new" lane
trick was intentionally used in a handful of tests where two or more
updates need to be scheduled in different lanes. Most of these tests
were written before `startTransition` existed, and all of them were
written before transitions were assigned arbitrary lanes.

So I ported these tests to use `startTransition` instead, which is the
idiomatic way to mark an update as parallel.

I didn't change the old fork at all. Writing these tests in such a way
that they also pass in the old fork actually revealed a few flaws in the
current implementation regarding interrupting a suspended refresh
transition early, which is a good reminder that we should be writing our
tests using idiomatic patterns as much as we possibly can.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/CrazyForks/react/commits/6c526c5153bc350d2a62c7dcbc698be77d3f2439"}]

XLA has its own test case class separate from TensorFlowTestCase.

forcibly disabled. None indicates the user didn't specify a preference.

Update the XLATestCase class to only disable the mlir bridge when
is_mlir_bridge_enabled() is False.

[{"sha":"6c526c5153bc350d2a62c7dcbc698be77d3f2439","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Don't shift interleaved updates to separate lane (#20681)

Now that interleaved updates are added to a special queue, we no longer
need to shift them into their own lane. We can add to a lane that's
already in the middle of rendering without risk of tearing.

See #20615 for more background.

I've only changed this in the new fork, and only behind the
enableTransitionEntanglements flag.

Most of this commit involves updating tests. The "shift-to-a-new" lane
trick was intentionally used in a handful of tests where two or more
updates need to be scheduled in different lanes. Most of these tests
were written before `startTransition` existed, and all of them were
written before transitions were assigned arbitrary lanes.

So I ported these tests to use `startTransition` instead, which is the
idiomatic way to mark an update as parallel.

I didn't change the old fork at all. Writing these tests in such a way
that they also pass in the old fork actually revealed a few flaws in the
current implementation regarding interrupting a suspended refresh
transition early, which is a good reminder that we should be writing our
tests using idiomatic patterns as much as we possibly can.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/wadezhan/react/commits/6c526c5153bc350d2a62c7dcbc698be77d3f2439"}]

[{"sha":"6c526c5153bc350d2a62c7dcbc698be77d3f2439","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Don't shift interleaved updates to separate lane (#20681)

Now that interleaved updates are added to a special queue, we no longer
need to shift them into their own lane. We can add to a lane that's
already in the middle of rendering without risk of tearing.

See #20615 for more background.

I've only changed this in the new fork, and only behind the
enableTransitionEntanglements flag.

Most of this commit involves updating tests. The "shift-to-a-new" lane
trick was intentionally used in a handful of tests where two or more
updates need to be scheduled in different lanes. Most of these tests
were written before `startTransition` existed, and all of them were
written before transitions were assigned arbitrary lanes.

So I ported these tests to use `startTransition` instead, which is the
idiomatic way to mark an update as parallel.

I didn't change the old fork at all. Writing these tests in such a way
that they also pass in the old fork actually revealed a few flaws in the
current implementation regarding interrupting a suspended refresh
transition early, which is a good reminder that we should be writing our
tests using idiomatic patterns as much as we possibly can.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/linbingquan/react/commits/6c526c5153bc350d2a62c7dcbc698be77d3f2439"}]

[{"sha":"d7cbf8f1fce4ba44d2a5a4e075b0a19f8885f6ce","author":{"name":"Philip Sahli","email":"3ba3974e96044dcde818e6310ed799abe10671d4@sahli.net"},"message":"Fix typo","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/NeatNerdPrime/terraform/commits/d7cbf8f1fce4ba44d2a5a4e075b0a19f8885f6ce"},{"sha":"4991cc48354275f5a190b12e0f8cdafb952fdc0a","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"cli: Improve error for invalid -target flags

Errors encountered when parsing flags for apply, plan, and refresh were
being suppressed. This resulted in a generic usage error when using an
invalid `-target` flag.

This commit makes several changes to address this. First, these commands
now output the flag parse error before exiting, leaving at least some
hint about the error. You can verify this manually with something like:

    terraform apply -invalid-flag

We also change how target attributes are parsed, moving the
responsibility from the flags instance to the command. This allows us to
customize the diagnostic output to be more user friendly. The
diagnostics now look like:

```shellsession
$ terraform apply -no-color -target=foo

Error: Invalid target "foo"

Resource specification must include a resource type and name.
```

Finally, we add test coverage for both parsing of target flags, and at
the command level for successful use of resource targeting. These tests
focus on the UI output (via the change summary and refresh logs), as the
functionality of targeting is covered by the context tests in the
terraform package.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/NeatNerdPrime/terraform/commits/4991cc48354275f5a190b12e0f8cdafb952fdc0a"},{"sha":"96be094ecdc9e7c1350aac198c64fa4f5776cfe0","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Merge pull request #27711 from hashicorp/alisdair/fix-target-flag-parsing-and-add-tests

[{"sha":"6c526c5153bc350d2a62c7dcbc698be77d3f2439","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Don't shift interleaved updates to separate lane (#20681)

Now that interleaved updates are added to a special queue, we no longer
need to shift them into their own lane. We can add to a lane that's
already in the middle of rendering without risk of tearing.

See #20615 for more background.

I've only changed this in the new fork, and only behind the
enableTransitionEntanglements flag.

Most of this commit involves updating tests. The "shift-to-a-new" lane
trick was intentionally used in a handful of tests where two or more
updates need to be scheduled in different lanes. Most of these tests
were written before `startTransition` existed, and all of them were
written before transitions were assigned arbitrary lanes.

So I ported these tests to use `startTransition` instead, which is the
idiomatic way to mark an update as parallel.

I didn't change the old fork at all. Writing these tests in such a way
that they also pass in the old fork actually revealed a few flaws in the
current implementation regarding interrupting a suspended refresh
transition early, which is a good reminder that we should be writing our
tests using idiomatic patterns as much as we possibly can.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/miqdigital/react/commits/6c526c5153bc350d2a62c7dcbc698be77d3f2439"}]

This PR is part of the effort to switch to modular file system support
by deprecates hdfs file system and direct user to use modular file system
from tensorflow-io instead.

[{"sha":"6c526c5153bc350d2a62c7dcbc698be77d3f2439","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Don't shift interleaved updates to separate lane (#20681)

Now that interleaved updates are added to a special queue, we no longer
need to shift them into their own lane. We can add to a lane that's
already in the middle of rendering without risk of tearing.

See #20615 for more background.

I've only changed this in the new fork, and only behind the
enableTransitionEntanglements flag.

Most of this commit involves updating tests. The "shift-to-a-new" lane
trick was intentionally used in a handful of tests where two or more
updates need to be scheduled in different lanes. Most of these tests
were written before `startTransition` existed, and all of them were
written before transitions were assigned arbitrary lanes.

So I ported these tests to use `startTransition` instead, which is the
idiomatic way to mark an update as parallel.

I didn't change the old fork at all. Writing these tests in such a way
that they also pass in the old fork actually revealed a few flaws in the
current implementation regarding interrupting a suspended refresh
transition early, which is a good reminder that we should be writing our
tests using idiomatic patterns as much as we possibly can.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/gaearon/react/commits/6c526c5153bc350d2a62c7dcbc698be77d3f2439"},{"sha":"8da9a8a69255acc8835af036bdfc6a2a12fd72ab","author":{"name":"Dan Abramov","email":"ffbbe9cb1097e7ea6a3dedffde5b4fe769829acc@me.com"},"message":"Add the feature flag","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/gaearon/react/commits/8da9a8a69255acc8835af036bdfc6a2a12fd72ab"},{"sha":"43ff9670f1c482d5ccb64e9377d2b58796195c26","author":{"name":"Dan Abramov","email":"ffbbe9cb1097e7ea6a3dedffde5b4fe769829acc@me.com"},"message":"Add a host config method","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/gaearon/react/commits/43ff9670f1c482d5ccb64e9377d2b58796195c26"},{"sha":"385c20f822bb255434f20303f9255363834eeaab","author":{"name":"Dan Abramov","email":"ffbbe9cb1097e7ea6a3dedffde5b4fe769829acc@me.com"},"message":"Wire it up to the work loop","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/gaearon/react/commits/385c20f822bb255434f20303f9255363834eeaab"},{"sha":"3cf8af7c4c561faea9a72c26db4743a548368837","author":{"name":"Dan Abramov","email":"ffbbe9cb1097e7ea6a3dedffde5b4fe769829acc@me.com"},"message":"Put constants behind react-reconciler export","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/gaearon/react/commits/3cf8af7c4c561faea9a72c26db4743a548368837"},{"sha":"18f51bcacb65b532acafd7ece676f36ce39f0023","author":{"name":"Dan Abramov","email":"ffbbe9cb1097e7ea6a3dedffde5b4fe769829acc@me.com"},"message":"Document for third-party renderers","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/gaearon/react/commits/18f51bcacb65b532acafd7ece676f36ce39f0023"}]

[{"sha":"d7cbf8f1fce4ba44d2a5a4e075b0a19f8885f6ce","author":{"name":"Philip Sahli","email":"3ba3974e96044dcde818e6310ed799abe10671d4@sahli.net"},"message":"Fix typo","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/avmi/terraform/commits/d7cbf8f1fce4ba44d2a5a4e075b0a19f8885f6ce"},{"sha":"4991cc48354275f5a190b12e0f8cdafb952fdc0a","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"cli: Improve error for invalid -target flags

Errors encountered when parsing flags for apply, plan, and refresh were
being suppressed. This resulted in a generic usage error when using an
invalid `-target` flag.

This commit makes several changes to address this. First, these commands
now output the flag parse error before exiting, leaving at least some
hint about the error. You can verify this manually with something like:

    terraform apply -invalid-flag

We also change how target attributes are parsed, moving the
responsibility from the flags instance to the command. This allows us to
customize the diagnostic output to be more user friendly. The
diagnostics now look like:

```shellsession
$ terraform apply -no-color -target=foo

Error: Invalid target "foo"

Resource specification must include a resource type and name.
```

Finally, we add test coverage for both parsing of target flags, and at
the command level for successful use of resource targeting. These tests
focus on the UI output (via the change summary and refresh logs), as the
functionality of targeting is covered by the context tests in the
terraform package.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/avmi/terraform/commits/4991cc48354275f5a190b12e0f8cdafb952fdc0a"},{"sha":"96be094ecdc9e7c1350aac198c64fa4f5776cfe0","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Merge pull request #27711 from hashicorp/alisdair/fix-target-flag-parsing-and-add-tests

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Adding support to identify a subset of possible auxiliary
induction variables (AIV). Specifically, candidates are gtes, e.g.,
gte(param0, N). We check if the loop body plumbs the AIV
through the same tuple index at root, and that ops involving AIV
involve constants.
   op2 = op(constants, gte(param0, N), constants)
   op3 = op(constants, f(op2, gte(param0, N), constants)
   root = tuple(..., op3, ...)
Further, the ops are restricted to basic math ops (+,-,*,/).

Currently we always assign the same lane to all transitions. This means
if there are two pending transitions at the same time, neither
transition can finish until both can finish, even if they affect
completely separate parts of the UI.

The new approach is to assign a different lane to each consecutive
transition, by shifting the bit to the right each time. When we reach
the end of the bit range, we cycle back to the first bit. In practice,
this should mean that all transitions get their own dedicated lane,
unless we have more pending transitions than lanes, which should
be rare.

We retain our existing behavior of assigning the same lane to all
transitions within the same event. This is achieved by caching the first
lane assigned to a transition, then re-using that one until the next
React task, by which point the event must have finished. This preserves
the guarantee that all transition updates that result from a single
event will be consistent.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/apshada/react/commits/a014c915c77f908ba3be3de9e6a06d05c71d5b62"},{"sha":"b4658f2daa4990ef8057335cd7202b479bd8d41a","author":{"name":"Dan Abramov","email":"ffbbe9cb1097e7ea6a3dedffde5b4fe769829acc@gmail.com"},"message":"Reduce some constant duplication (#20761)

[{"sha":"6c526c5153bc350d2a62c7dcbc698be77d3f2439","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Don't shift interleaved updates to separate lane (#20681)

Now that interleaved updates are added to a special queue, we no longer
need to shift them into their own lane. We can add to a lane that's
already in the middle of rendering without risk of tearing.

See #20615 for more background.

I've only changed this in the new fork, and only behind the
enableTransitionEntanglements flag.

Most of this commit involves updating tests. The "shift-to-a-new" lane
trick was intentionally used in a handful of tests where two or more
updates need to be scheduled in different lanes. Most of these tests
were written before `startTransition` existed, and all of them were
written before transitions were assigned arbitrary lanes.

So I ported these tests to use `startTransition` instead, which is the
idiomatic way to mark an update as parallel.

I didn't change the old fork at all. Writing these tests in such a way
that they also pass in the old fork actually revealed a few flaws in the
current implementation regarding interrupting a suspended refresh
transition early, which is a good reminder that we should be writing our
tests using idiomatic patterns as much as we possibly can.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/YashKumarVerma/react/commits/6c526c5153bc350d2a62c7dcbc698be77d3f2439"}]

The pattern is common is TF python library like height = tf.shape(x)[1].
When x has some dynamic dimensions (typically batch dim), tf.shape can not be constant folded so height cannot be inferred as a constant.
This PR folds this kind of patterns to improve sub-shape constant folding.

[{"sha":"6c526c5153bc350d2a62c7dcbc698be77d3f2439","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Don't shift interleaved updates to separate lane (#20681)

Now that interleaved updates are added to a special queue, we no longer
need to shift them into their own lane. We can add to a lane that's
already in the middle of rendering without risk of tearing.

See #20615 for more background.

I've only changed this in the new fork, and only behind the
enableTransitionEntanglements flag.

Most of this commit involves updating tests. The "shift-to-a-new" lane
trick was intentionally used in a handful of tests where two or more
updates need to be scheduled in different lanes. Most of these tests
were written before `startTransition` existed, and all of them were
written before transitions were assigned arbitrary lanes.

So I ported these tests to use `startTransition` instead, which is the
idiomatic way to mark an update as parallel.

I didn't change the old fork at all. Writing these tests in such a way
that they also pass in the old fork actually revealed a few flaws in the
current implementation regarding interrupting a suspended refresh
transition early, which is a good reminder that we should be writing our
tests using idiomatic patterns as much as we possibly can.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/suddenlyGiovanni/react/commits/6c526c5153bc350d2a62c7dcbc698be77d3f2439"}]

IEEE 754, it makes writing tests much easier.

[{"sha":"4991cc48354275f5a190b12e0f8cdafb952fdc0a","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"cli: Improve error for invalid -target flags

Errors encountered when parsing flags for apply, plan, and refresh were
being suppressed. This resulted in a generic usage error when using an
invalid `-target` flag.

This commit makes several changes to address this. First, these commands
now output the flag parse error before exiting, leaving at least some
hint about the error. You can verify this manually with something like:

    terraform apply -invalid-flag

We also change how target attributes are parsed, moving the
responsibility from the flags instance to the command. This allows us to
customize the diagnostic output to be more user friendly. The
diagnostics now look like:

```shellsession
$ terraform apply -no-color -target=foo

Error: Invalid target "foo"

Resource specification must include a resource type and name.
```

Finally, we add test coverage for both parsing of target flags, and at
the command level for successful use of resource targeting. These tests
focus on the UI output (via the change summary and refresh logs), as the
functionality of targeting is covered by the context tests in the
terraform package.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/dweomer/terraform/commits/4991cc48354275f5a190b12e0f8cdafb952fdc0a"},{"sha":"96be094ecdc9e7c1350aac198c64fa4f5776cfe0","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Merge pull request #27711 from hashicorp/alisdair/fix-target-flag-parsing-and-add-tests

tf.strings.substr will crash when pos and len have different shapes.
According to the documentation of tf.strings.substr, ValueError
should be raised instead when pos and len does not have the same shape.

This PR add shape check in kernel to allows grace error throw (instead of crash).

This PR fixes 46900.

[{"sha":"6c526c5153bc350d2a62c7dcbc698be77d3f2439","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Don't shift interleaved updates to separate lane (#20681)

Now that interleaved updates are added to a special queue, we no longer
need to shift them into their own lane. We can add to a lane that's
already in the middle of rendering without risk of tearing.

See #20615 for more background.

I've only changed this in the new fork, and only behind the
enableTransitionEntanglements flag.

Most of this commit involves updating tests. The "shift-to-a-new" lane
trick was intentionally used in a handful of tests where two or more
updates need to be scheduled in different lanes. Most of these tests
were written before `startTransition` existed, and all of them were
written before transitions were assigned arbitrary lanes.

So I ported these tests to use `startTransition` instead, which is the
idiomatic way to mark an update as parallel.

I didn't change the old fork at all. Writing these tests in such a way
that they also pass in the old fork actually revealed a few flaws in the
current implementation regarding interrupting a suspended refresh
transition early, which is a good reminder that we should be writing our
tests using idiomatic patterns as much as we possibly can.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JochLAin/react/commits/6c526c5153bc350d2a62c7dcbc698be77d3f2439"}]

[{"sha":"a014c915c77f908ba3be3de9e6a06d05c71d5b62","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Parallel transitions: Assign different lanes to consecutive transitions (#20672)

* Land enableTransitionEntanglement changes

Leaving the flag though because I plan to reuse it for additional,
similar changes.

* Assign different lanes to consecutive transitions

Currently we always assign the same lane to all transitions. This means
if there are two pending transitions at the same time, neither
transition can finish until both can finish, even if they affect
completely separate parts of the UI.

The new approach is to assign a different lane to each consecutive
transition, by shifting the bit to the right each time. When we reach
the end of the bit range, we cycle back to the first bit. In practice,
this should mean that all transitions get their own dedicated lane,
unless we have more pending transitions than lanes, which should
be rare.

We retain our existing behavior of assigning the same lane to all
transitions within the same event. This is achieved by caching the first
lane assigned to a transition, then re-using that one until the next
React task, by which point the event must have finished. This preserves
the guarantee that all transition updates that result from a single
event will be consistent.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Qwerty0x64/react/commits/a014c915c77f908ba3be3de9e6a06d05c71d5b62"},{"sha":"b4658f2daa4990ef8057335cd7202b479bd8d41a","author":{"name":"Dan Abramov","email":"ffbbe9cb1097e7ea6a3dedffde5b4fe769829acc@gmail.com"},"message":"Reduce some constant duplication (#20761)

The pattern is common is TF python library like height = tf.shape(x)[1].
When x has some dynamic dimensions (typically batch dim), tf.shape can not be constant folded so height cannot be inferred as a constant.
This PR folds this kind of patterns to improve sub-shape constant folding.

[{"sha":"6c526c5153bc350d2a62c7dcbc698be77d3f2439","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Don't shift interleaved updates to separate lane (#20681)

Now that interleaved updates are added to a special queue, we no longer
need to shift them into their own lane. We can add to a lane that's
already in the middle of rendering without risk of tearing.

See #20615 for more background.

I've only changed this in the new fork, and only behind the
enableTransitionEntanglements flag.

Most of this commit involves updating tests. The "shift-to-a-new" lane
trick was intentionally used in a handful of tests where two or more
updates need to be scheduled in different lanes. Most of these tests
were written before `startTransition` existed, and all of them were
written before transitions were assigned arbitrary lanes.

So I ported these tests to use `startTransition` instead, which is the
idiomatic way to mark an update as parallel.

I didn't change the old fork at all. Writing these tests in such a way
that they also pass in the old fork actually revealed a few flaws in the
current implementation regarding interrupting a suspended refresh
transition early, which is a good reminder that we should be writing our
tests using idiomatic patterns as much as we possibly can.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Jeffkeen7/react/commits/6c526c5153bc350d2a62c7dcbc698be77d3f2439"}]

This PR tries to address the issue raised in 46900 where
tf.strings.substr will crash when pos and len have different shapes.
According to the documentation of tf.strings.substr, ValueError
should be raised instead when pos and len does not have the same shape.

This PR add shape check in kernel to allows grace error throw (instead of crash).

This PR fixes 46900.

This PR folds this kind of patterns to improve sub-shape constant folding.

Change-Id: Ib4dc25f9ce7bfe729bf19da6a92e0102518f502a","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/UofT-EcoSystem/tensorflow/commits/e1b9195cae5640ae158ebf9496787b6d511bad63"},{"sha":"417c2d448c11709696cf69a1d241b38955120f5f","author":{"name":"Marissa Ikonomidis","email":"dfdd147e0d31ffa94f60174fe3bbdbabee0568c5@google.com"},"message":"Fix XLATestCase enable mlir bridge logic

XLA has its own test case class separate from TensorFlowTestCase.
The XLATestCase was not differentiating between is_mlir_bridge_enabled()
returning False vs None. False indicates that the mlir bridge was
forcibly disabled. None indicates the user didn't specify a preference.

Update the XLATestCase class to only disable the mlir bridge when
is_mlir_bridge_enabled() is False.

The default behavior is that NaN != NaN, making it impossible to check
values against known good values that contains NaN. Change the behavior
so NaN is equal (and close) to just NaN. While this is incompatible with
IEEE 754, it makes writing tests much easier.

The pattern is common is TF python library like height = tf.shape(x)[1].
When x has some dynamic dimensions (typically batch dim), tf.shape can not be constant folded so height cannot be inferred as a constant.
This PR folds this kind of patterns to improve sub-shape constant folding.

[{"sha":"6c526c5153bc350d2a62c7dcbc698be77d3f2439","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Don't shift interleaved updates to separate lane (#20681)

Now that interleaved updates are added to a special queue, we no longer
need to shift them into their own lane. We can add to a lane that's
already in the middle of rendering without risk of tearing.

See #20615 for more background.

I've only changed this in the new fork, and only behind the
enableTransitionEntanglements flag.

Most of this commit involves updating tests. The "shift-to-a-new" lane
trick was intentionally used in a handful of tests where two or more
updates need to be scheduled in different lanes. Most of these tests
were written before `startTransition` existed, and all of them were
written before transitions were assigned arbitrary lanes.

So I ported these tests to use `startTransition` instead, which is the
idiomatic way to mark an update as parallel.

I didn't change the old fork at all. Writing these tests in such a way
that they also pass in the old fork actually revealed a few flaws in the
current implementation regarding interrupting a suspended refresh
transition early, which is a good reminder that we should be writing our
tests using idiomatic patterns as much as we possibly can.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/SimenB/react/commits/6c526c5153bc350d2a62c7dcbc698be77d3f2439"}]

[{"sha":"62a1fad4fa6955edfa8004e98c8dff51ecd3d18a","author":{"name":"A. Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Adding support to identify a subset of possible auxiliary
induction variables (AIV). Specifically, candidates are gtes, e.g.,
gte(param0, N). We check if the loop body plumbs the AIV
through the same tuple index at root, and that ops involving AIV
involve constants.
   op2 = op(constants, gte(param0, N), constants)
   op3 = op(constants, f(op2, gte(param0, N), constants)
   root = tuple(..., op3, ...)
Further, the ops are restricted to basic math ops (+,-,*,/).

The pattern is common is TF python library like height = tf.shape(x)[1].
When x has some dynamic dimensions (typically batch dim), tf.shape can not be constant folded so height cannot be inferred as a constant.
This PR folds this kind of patterns to improve sub-shape constant folding.

[{"sha":"6c526c5153bc350d2a62c7dcbc698be77d3f2439","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Don't shift interleaved updates to separate lane (#20681)

Now that interleaved updates are added to a special queue, we no longer
need to shift them into their own lane. We can add to a lane that's
already in the middle of rendering without risk of tearing.

See #20615 for more background.

I've only changed this in the new fork, and only behind the
enableTransitionEntanglements flag.

Most of this commit involves updating tests. The "shift-to-a-new" lane
trick was intentionally used in a handful of tests where two or more
updates need to be scheduled in different lanes. Most of these tests
were written before `startTransition` existed, and all of them were
written before transitions were assigned arbitrary lanes.

So I ported these tests to use `startTransition` instead, which is the
idiomatic way to mark an update as parallel.

I didn't change the old fork at all. Writing these tests in such a way
that they also pass in the old fork actually revealed a few flaws in the
current implementation regarding interrupting a suspended refresh
transition early, which is a good reminder that we should be writing our
tests using idiomatic patterns as much as we possibly can.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/db-apps/react/commits/6c526c5153bc350d2a62c7dcbc698be77d3f2439"}]

[{"sha":"6c526c5153bc350d2a62c7dcbc698be77d3f2439","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Don't shift interleaved updates to separate lane (#20681)

Now that interleaved updates are added to a special queue, we no longer
need to shift them into their own lane. We can add to a lane that's
already in the middle of rendering without risk of tearing.

See #20615 for more background.

I've only changed this in the new fork, and only behind the
enableTransitionEntanglements flag.

Most of this commit involves updating tests. The "shift-to-a-new" lane
trick was intentionally used in a handful of tests where two or more
updates need to be scheduled in different lanes. Most of these tests
were written before `startTransition` existed, and all of them were
written before transitions were assigned arbitrary lanes.

So I ported these tests to use `startTransition` instead, which is the
idiomatic way to mark an update as parallel.

I didn't change the old fork at all. Writing these tests in such a way
that they also pass in the old fork actually revealed a few flaws in the
current implementation regarding interrupting a suspended refresh
transition early, which is a good reminder that we should be writing our
tests using idiomatic patterns as much as we possibly can.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tbergq/react/commits/6c526c5153bc350d2a62c7dcbc698be77d3f2439"}]

tf.strings.substr will crash when pos and len have different shapes.

[{"sha":"6c526c5153bc350d2a62c7dcbc698be77d3f2439","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Don't shift interleaved updates to separate lane (#20681)

Now that interleaved updates are added to a special queue, we no longer
need to shift them into their own lane. We can add to a lane that's
already in the middle of rendering without risk of tearing.

See #20615 for more background.

I've only changed this in the new fork, and only behind the
enableTransitionEntanglements flag.

Most of this commit involves updating tests. The "shift-to-a-new" lane
trick was intentionally used in a handful of tests where two or more
updates need to be scheduled in different lanes. Most of these tests
were written before `startTransition` existed, and all of them were
written before transitions were assigned arbitrary lanes.

So I ported these tests to use `startTransition` instead, which is the
idiomatic way to mark an update as parallel.

I didn't change the old fork at all. Writing these tests in such a way
that they also pass in the old fork actually revealed a few flaws in the
current implementation regarding interrupting a suspended refresh
transition early, which is a good reminder that we should be writing our
tests using idiomatic patterns as much as we possibly can.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JCofman/react/commits/6c526c5153bc350d2a62c7dcbc698be77d3f2439"}]

* Land enableTransitionEntanglement changes

Leaving the flag though because I plan to reuse it for additional,
similar changes.

* Assign different lanes to consecutive transitions

Currently we always assign the same lane to all transitions. This means
if there are two pending transitions at the same time, neither
transition can finish until both can finish, even if they affect
completely separate parts of the UI.

The new approach is to assign a different lane to each consecutive
transition, by shifting the bit to the right each time. When we reach
the end of the bit range, we cycle back to the first bit. In practice,
this should mean that all transitions get their own dedicated lane,
unless we have more pending transitions than lanes, which should
be rare.

We retain our existing behavior of assigning the same lane to all
transitions within the same event. This is achieved by caching the first
lane assigned to a transition, then re-using that one until the next
React task, by which point the event must have finished. This preserves
the guarantee that all transition updates that result from a single
event will be consistent.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mahak/react/commits/a014c915c77f908ba3be3de9e6a06d05c71d5b62"},{"sha":"b4658f2daa4990ef8057335cd7202b479bd8d41a","author":{"name":"Dan Abramov","email":"ffbbe9cb1097e7ea6a3dedffde5b4fe769829acc@gmail.com"},"message":"Reduce some constant duplication (#20761)

A running GMainLoop processes many events on the GLib/GStreamer
world. While some things may work without it, many others wont.
Examples of these are signals, timers and many other source
events. The problem becomes more concerning by the fact that
some GStreamer elements rely on signals to work.

This commit allows the user to specify an OpenCV option to
start a main loop, if needed. Since the loop blocks, this is

[{"sha":"6c526c5153bc350d2a62c7dcbc698be77d3f2439","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Don't shift interleaved updates to separate lane (#20681)

Now that interleaved updates are added to a special queue, we no longer
need to shift them into their own lane. We can add to a lane that's
already in the middle of rendering without risk of tearing.

See #20615 for more background.

I've only changed this in the new fork, and only behind the
enableTransitionEntanglements flag.

Most of this commit involves updating tests. The "shift-to-a-new" lane
trick was intentionally used in a handful of tests where two or more
updates need to be scheduled in different lanes. Most of these tests
were written before `startTransition` existed, and all of them were
written before transitions were assigned arbitrary lanes.

So I ported these tests to use `startTransition` instead, which is the
idiomatic way to mark an update as parallel.

I didn't change the old fork at all. Writing these tests in such a way
that they also pass in the old fork actually revealed a few flaws in the
current implementation regarding interrupting a suspended refresh
transition early, which is a good reminder that we should be writing our
tests using idiomatic patterns as much as we possibly can.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/gouda1a1/react/commits/6c526c5153bc350d2a62c7dcbc698be77d3f2439"}]

artifacts directory.

The script works by wrapping the existing build script (which only
builds a single release channel at a time), then post-processing the
results to match the desired filesystem layout. A future version of the
build script would output the files directly without post-processing.

We need to call `detachFiberAfterEffects` on the fiber's alternate to
clean it up. We're currently not, because the `alternate` field is
cleared during `detachFiberMutation`. So I deferred detaching the
`alternate` until the passive phase. Only the `return` pointer needs to
be detached for semantic purposes.

I don't think there's any good way to test this without using
reflection. It's not even observable using out our "supported"
reflection APIs (`findDOMNode`), or at least not that I can think of.
Which is a good thing, in a way.

It's not really a memory leak, either, because the only reference to the
alternate fiber is from the parent's alternate. Which will be
disconnected the next time the parent is updated or deleted.

It's really only observable if you mess around with internals in ways
you're not supposed to — I found it because a product test in www that
uses Enzyme was doing just that.
